\pard\f0\fs28   In E. Europe the plants are predominantly without stolons; in W.C. Europe, most plants have stolons, with the stem rooting at the base. Many of the former have been shown to be tetraploid, and of the latter diploid. The eastern plants appear in Poland and elsewhere to be connected with {\b 62} by intermediates; the exact boundary between {\b 62} and{\b  63} has yet to be established. The plants from the Iberian peninsula may represent a distinct taxon.
